# Heritage: manual version control only

The user bumps PDX Heritage Trees releases with [`heritage/version.ps1`](heritage/version.ps1). **Do not** change release or cache-bust version numbers as part of routine feature work, bugfixes, or refactors unless the user **explicitly** asks you to bump or set a version (e.g. “bump to 1.2.9”, “run version.ps1”, “update the version for release”).

**Do not run** `heritage/version.ps1` on your own after code changes.

**Leave unchanged without explicit instruction:**

- [`heritage/service-worker.js`](heritage/service-worker.js) — `VERSION` and cache names derived from it
- [`heritage/manifest.json`](heritage/manifest.json) — `version`
- [`heritage/js/app.js`](heritage/js/app.js) — `APP_VERSION`
- [`heritage/index.html`](heritage/index.html) — `?v=` on CSS/JS (and any other versioned asset query strings)

If new or changed scripts would not load until cache busting, **say so** and let the user run `version.ps1`; do not bump automatically.

When the user **does** request a version change, they normally run:

```powershell
pwsh -File heritage/version.ps1        # interactive
pwsh -File heritage/version.ps1 1.3.0  # explicit
pwsh -File heritage/version.ps1 -Rev   # patch increment
```

Only run that script for them when they explicitly ask. Do not hand-edit version strings in the four files unless they ask you to set a specific version without using the script.
